WEBVTT

00:04.960 --> 00:07.160
(BABY CRYING)

00:07.240 --> 00:09.200
(SPEAKS CHINESE DIALECT)

01:25.520 --> 01:27.160
Sir, this is her.

01:29.000 --> 01:30.440
The girl who tells fortunes?

01:45.320 --> 01:47.440
(FAINT WHISPERING)

02:03.400 --> 02:06.560
They're doing a magic spell.
To make it win a race.

02:13.840 --> 02:15.800
The horse's name is Monaghan Boy.

02:16.160 --> 02:18.240
Kempton. 3:00. Monday.

02:18.840 --> 02:21.680
You ladies have a bet yourselves,
but don't tell anyone else.

02:27.960 --> 02:29.840
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

02:47.600 --> 02:50.520
MAN: And Abraham
made his home in a cave.

02:50.600 --> 02:54.560
But it was good. Because
God resided there with him.

02:55.280 --> 03:01.120
You see, children, God does not care
if you live in a slum, or in a mansion.

03:01.720 --> 03:05.760
God does not care if you are rich,
or you are poor...

03:15.040 --> 03:16.040
Morning, sir.

03:25.720 --> 03:26.720
Morning, Mr Shelby.

04:10.440 --> 04:12.040
-Come on, lad.
-Good day, sir.

04:13.480 --> 04:15.800
-Morning, Mr Shelby.
-Sir.

04:19.720 --> 04:20.800
MAN: Good day, Mr Shelby.

04:31.600 --> 04:32.600
Finn?

04:35.360 --> 04:36.840
Arthur's mad as hell.

04:41.000 --> 04:43.200
What does a 10-year-old
know about hell? Eh?

04:43.440 --> 04:44.800
I'm 11 Sunday.

04:51.520 --> 04:53.320
(MEN CALLING OUT)

04:56.640 --> 04:57.720
I'm looking for Tommy.

04:57.800 --> 05:00.720
BOOKIE: Get your bets in now
for the 2:30 at Kempton.

05:00.800 --> 05:02.640
Right, what we got on Percy Piper?

05:02.720 --> 05:06.280
Piper going well in the soft, lads.
Down to fours.

05:06.360 --> 05:07.640
Fours.

05:07.720 --> 05:10.200
-Okay, Monaghan Boy?
-Wanna push that down, mate.

05:10.280 --> 05:11.280
Two to one, still.

05:18.080 --> 05:20.480
Two to one. Get your bets in now.

05:20.560 --> 05:23.040
What do you say? We got Topper in,
he's an old favourite.

05:23.120 --> 05:24.480
Four to one.

05:27.080 --> 05:28.600
Tommy! Tommy!

05:28.880 --> 05:31.120
Tommy, look at the book.
Just look.

05:31.600 --> 05:33.120
-ARTHUR: Tommy!
-All on Monaghan Boy.

05:33.200 --> 05:34.880
-Good work, John.
-Tommy!

05:35.640 --> 05:37.160
Get in here. Now.

05:38.480 --> 05:39.840
BOOKIE: That'll be six pennies, nipper.

05:40.360 --> 05:41.880
That's ten bob you'll see for that.

05:50.920 --> 05:55.240
Now, you were seen doing the
powder trick down at Garrison Courts.

05:56.200 --> 05:57.200
Times are hard.

05:58.160 --> 05:59.640
People need a reason to lay a bet.

06:00.320 --> 06:01.440
There was a Chinese.

06:02.240 --> 06:04.200
The washerwomen say she's a witch.

06:05.280 --> 06:08.000
-It helps them believe.
-We don't mess with Chinese.

06:08.480 --> 06:12.680
-Look at the book.
-Chinese have cutters of their own.

06:13.120 --> 06:14.600
We agreed, Arthur.

06:15.360 --> 06:17.760
I'm taking charge
of drumming up their money.

06:20.640 --> 06:22.440
What if Monaghan Boy wins, Tommy?

06:23.480 --> 06:24.800
You fixing races now?

06:25.640 --> 06:28.880
Do you have permission from Billy Kimber
to be fixing races? Hmm?

06:30.880 --> 06:32.360
And what's got into you?

06:33.680 --> 06:38.120
You think we can take on
the Chinese and Billy Kimber?

06:38.360 --> 06:42.240
-Billy's got a bloody army!
-I think, Arthur.

06:43.360 --> 06:44.760
That's what I do.

06:48.520 --> 06:49.760
I think.

06:51.040 --> 06:53.160
So that you don't have to.

06:57.200 --> 06:58.600
There's news from Belfast.

07:04.720 --> 07:07.520
I'm calling a family council tonight
at 8:00.

07:07.840 --> 07:08.960
I want all of us there.

07:09.840 --> 07:11.120
You hear me?

07:11.520 --> 07:12.920
There's trouble coming.

07:13.040 --> 07:14.840
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

07:58.720 --> 08:00.520
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

08:12.520 --> 08:14.720
All right, shut up now.
Shut up.

08:16.800 --> 08:20.880
Comrades, we're here today
to take a vote on strike action.

08:20.960 --> 08:22.040
MEN: Yes!

08:23.360 --> 08:25.160
But before we have a
show of hands for that,

08:26.600 --> 08:29.240
let's have a show of hands from
all those who fought in France.

08:29.720 --> 08:32.520
All those who stood side by side
with your comrades,

08:33.000 --> 08:34.720
and watched your comrades fall.

08:35.520 --> 08:37.120
Raise your hands.

08:41.400 --> 08:44.400
The blood shed on Flanders Fields.

08:44.960 --> 08:46.840
The sweat of your brows.

08:48.040 --> 08:49.480
Who reaps the rewards?

08:50.120 --> 08:51.120
Is it you?

08:51.200 --> 08:52.560
-No, no.
-No!

08:52.640 --> 08:53.680
Is it your wives?

08:53.760 --> 08:55.120
-No, no.
-No, no.

08:55.240 --> 08:56.960
Well, who then?
Do they stand among us?

08:57.040 --> 08:58.040
-No!
-No!

08:58.200 --> 09:01.800
Or do they sit at home,
comfortable, with a full belly?

09:02.200 --> 09:07.120
While you scrape to find enough
to put shoes on your children's feet!

09:07.200 --> 09:10.520
And what is the reward they offer you
for your sacrifices made?

09:11.520 --> 09:13.760
A fucking cut in your wages!

09:14.040 --> 09:15.200
That is your reward!

09:16.360 --> 09:18.680
Raise a hand,
all those who want to strike!

09:18.760 --> 09:21.480
-Yes! Yes!
-Yes! Yes!

10:14.120 --> 10:15.320
On the house, Mr Shelby.

10:36.160 --> 10:37.640
-I'll take a mild.
-Right.

10:57.960 --> 10:58.960
Cheers, Thomas.

11:00.040 --> 11:01.040
Good health to you.

11:07.440 --> 11:08.560
Crown of a prince.

11:12.520 --> 11:14.920
-Soon to be king, I'd bet.
-You don't bet.

11:15.720 --> 11:18.520
No, but these past few days
I've been speculating.

11:22.840 --> 11:23.840
About what?

11:24.880 --> 11:26.840
One of my union comrades has a sister.

11:27.200 --> 11:29.760
Works in the telegraph office
at the BSA factory.

11:30.640 --> 11:32.120
She says, over the past week,

11:32.200 --> 11:34.520
they've had messages coming up
from London to the brass.

11:35.360 --> 11:36.840
From Winston Churchill himself.

11:42.080 --> 11:43.640
Something about a robbery.

11:44.960 --> 11:47.520
A robbery of national significance,
it's said.

11:50.280 --> 11:52.000
She found a list of names

11:52.080 --> 11:54.000
left in the telegraph machine.

11:55.800 --> 11:58.720
And on that list was your name
and my name together.

12:01.640 --> 12:03.360
What kind of a list would
have the name of a communist

12:03.440 --> 12:05.400
and the name of a bookmaker
side by side?

12:10.160 --> 12:13.800
Perhaps it's a list of men
who give false hope to the poor.

12:15.160 --> 12:17.560
The only difference between
you and me, Freddie,

12:17.640 --> 12:19.840
is that, sometimes...

12:19.920 --> 12:21.480
my horses stand a chance of winning.

12:29.440 --> 12:30.720
You know, there are days -

12:30.800 --> 12:32.560
when I hear about
the cuttings and beatings -

12:32.640 --> 12:35.520
that I really wish I'd let you
take that bullet in France.

12:37.360 --> 12:40.440
Believe me,
there are nights I wish you had.

12:43.520 --> 12:44.680
Hey!

12:49.240 --> 12:50.360
They're gonna kill me!

12:50.440 --> 12:52.800
On three! One, two, three, go!

12:54.920 --> 12:56.320
Breathe, Danny. Breathe!

12:56.400 --> 12:58.720
They're gonna kill me!
They're gonna kill me!

12:59.080 --> 13:02.120
-They're gonna kill me!
-Danny! Danny, Danny, you're home.

13:02.200 --> 13:03.720
We're all home in England.

13:03.800 --> 13:05.120
You're not in France.

13:05.600 --> 13:08.480
You're not an artillery shell, Danny,
you're a man.

13:08.560 --> 13:09.720
Eh?

13:09.800 --> 13:12.680
You're not a whizz-bang,
you're a human being, Danny.

13:13.080 --> 13:15.680
You're all right.
You're all right.

13:16.280 --> 13:17.320
You're all right.

13:17.720 --> 13:19.360
Up, Up!

13:20.320 --> 13:21.320
(WHIMPERS)

13:23.320 --> 13:24.440
It's all right.

13:25.520 --> 13:26.520
It's all right.

13:29.520 --> 13:30.720
Oh, hell.

13:31.240 --> 13:32.480
Did I do it again?

13:33.920 --> 13:35.520
You did it again, Danny.

13:38.800 --> 13:40.760
You gotta stop doing this, man.

13:42.120 --> 13:44.280
-He's all right.
-Oh God, Mr Shelby, I'm sorry.

13:44.360 --> 13:45.360
It's all right.

13:45.880 --> 13:47.800
-You go home to your wife now, Danny.
-Yeah.

13:48.240 --> 13:50.360
And get all that smoke and mud
out of your head, eh?

13:50.640 --> 13:53.000
Yes, Mr Shelby. I'm sorry.

13:54.200 --> 13:55.200
Go on.

13:59.760 --> 14:02.200
Mr Shelby, you have to do
something about him.

14:02.400 --> 14:03.680
Damn right, Harry.

14:03.760 --> 14:06.280
You pay the Peaky Blinders
a lot of money for protection.

14:07.960 --> 14:10.000
You're the law around here now, Tommy,
aren't you?

14:11.120 --> 14:13.080
Maybe you should put a bullet
in Danny Whizz-Bang's head

14:13.160 --> 14:15.160
like they do with mad horses.

14:17.440 --> 14:20.120
Maybe you'll have to put a bullet
in my head someday, too.

14:30.440 --> 14:32.240
Bring the bill to the Peaky Blinders.

14:32.720 --> 14:33.720
We'll take care of it.

14:53.720 --> 14:55.360
Look at the gun.

14:56.880 --> 14:58.920
-Recognise it?
-Mmm.

15:00.560 --> 15:01.600
(CRIES OUT)

15:01.680 --> 15:03.600
-Fuck!
-Get up off your arse, you mumping pig.

15:03.680 --> 15:06.280
Aunt Poll, what the fuck
did you do that for?

15:06.800 --> 15:09.320
Finn was playing with this
this afternoon by the cut.

15:09.400 --> 15:11.760
It was loaded.
Nearly blew Ada's tits off.

15:12.680 --> 15:13.840
It must have fell out of me pocket.

15:13.960 --> 15:16.040
He said he found it on the
sideboard of the betting shop.

15:16.160 --> 15:17.280
With bullets in it.

15:18.120 --> 15:19.120
I...

15:19.800 --> 15:20.800
I must have been drunk.

15:22.600 --> 15:23.720
When are you not drunk?

15:24.040 --> 15:25.960
Look, Aunt Polly, I'm sorry.

15:26.720 --> 15:28.520
(STAMMERS) I'm... I'm sorry.

15:30.120 --> 15:31.840
We'll keep this between ourselves

15:31.920 --> 15:34.480
if you swear not to leave guns
lying around.

15:38.040 --> 15:41.200
Look, I know having four kids
without a woman is hard,

15:41.280 --> 15:43.080
but my boot's harder.
Now come on, were late.

15:45.000 --> 15:46.240
Right!

15:46.320 --> 15:49.800
I've called this family meeting because
I've got some very important news.

15:50.720 --> 15:53.720
Scudboat and Love lock
got back from Belfast last night.

15:54.880 --> 15:57.240
They were buying a stallion
to cover their mares.

15:58.120 --> 16:00.520
They were in a pub on the
Shankhill Road yesterday,

16:00.760 --> 16:03.600
and in that pub there was a copper.

16:04.480 --> 16:06.240
Handing out these.

16:09.040 --> 16:11.800
"If you're over five feet
and can fight, come to Birmingham."

16:13.520 --> 16:17.640
They're recruiting Protestant Irishmen
to come over here as Special.

16:17.800 --> 16:20.280
-To do what?
-To clean up the city, Ada.

16:20.920 --> 16:22.200
He's the Chief Inspector.

16:23.400 --> 16:26.920
The last four years, he's been
clearing the IRA out of Belfast.

16:27.280 --> 16:28.840
How do you know so bloody much?

16:29.360 --> 16:31.320
'Cause I asked the coppers
on our payroll.

16:31.880 --> 16:33.040
And why didn't you tell me?

16:35.360 --> 16:36.360
I'm telling you.

16:38.840 --> 16:40.400
So why are they sending him
to Birmingham?

16:40.720 --> 16:43.160
Well, there's been all these
bloody strikes at the BSA.

16:43.480 --> 16:44.920
And the Austin works, lately.

16:45.840 --> 16:47.720
Now the papers
are talking about sedition.

16:48.520 --> 16:49.520
And revolution.

16:50.440 --> 16:52.000
I reckon it's communists he's after.

16:52.400 --> 16:54.520
So this copper's gonna
leave us alone, right?

16:55.520 --> 16:58.560
There are Irishmen in Green Lanes
who left Belfast to get away from him.

16:59.200 --> 17:02.040
They say Catholic men who crossed him
used to disappear in the night.

17:02.240 --> 17:03.400
Yeah, but we ain't IRA.

17:04.200 --> 17:05.760
We bloody fought for the King.

17:06.720 --> 17:08.120
Anyway, we're Peaky Blinders.

17:08.560 --> 17:09.800
We're not scared of coppers.

17:09.880 --> 17:11.680
-He's right.
-If they come for us,

17:11.880 --> 17:13.360
we'll cut them a smile each.

17:14.160 --> 17:15.640
So, Arthur. Is that it?

17:16.960 --> 17:18.320
ARTHUR:
What do you think, Aunt Poll?

17:19.080 --> 17:20.640
This family does everything open.

17:22.320 --> 17:24.240
You've nothing more to say
to this meeting, Thomas?

17:25.160 --> 17:26.160
No.

17:27.000 --> 17:28.360
Nothing that's women's business.

17:28.640 --> 17:30.640
This whole bloody enterprise
was women's business

17:30.720 --> 17:32.360
while you boys were away at war.

17:33.360 --> 17:34.360
What's changed?

17:35.640 --> 17:36.640
We came back.

17:37.360 --> 17:40.080
And the Lord will smite the unholy

17:40.160 --> 17:41.840
when the great judgement comes.

17:42.400 --> 17:44.400
And judgement is coming, my friends.

17:44.840 --> 17:47.920
Judgement is coming to this wicked city.

17:48.000 --> 17:52.520
And your wickedness
and your fornication will be revealed.

17:52.960 --> 17:55.560
You cannot hide from the Creator.

17:56.160 --> 17:59.560
You cannot hide
from the Almighty himself.

18:00.040 --> 18:01.720
The Creator sees all.

18:02.400 --> 18:05.440
You cannot hide
from the true and living God.

18:05.520 --> 18:07.400
Get off with ya!

18:11.720 --> 18:12.720
Ahh!

18:17.080 --> 18:18.200
Fuck off.

18:30.040 --> 18:31.400
(CHILD SHOUTING)

18:31.840 --> 18:33.760
That's it. I don't go any further.

18:36.440 --> 18:38.760
(CHILDREN SHOUTING)

18:51.000 --> 18:53.640
I have ten minutes.
What do you want?

18:58.320 --> 18:59.840
An explanation.

19:03.560 --> 19:07.000
Always been able to tell
when you're hiding something.

19:08.880 --> 19:10.480
People round here talk.

19:11.320 --> 19:13.040
Some of them work at the BSA.

19:14.280 --> 19:16.320
I've been talking to the wives
of factory hands.

19:16.400 --> 19:19.520
Detectives have been asking questions
in the proofing shops.

19:21.280 --> 19:24.680
Nothing happens in that factory
without you knowing about it.

19:25.360 --> 19:26.360
Speak.

19:27.640 --> 19:29.560
God and Aunt Polly are listening.

19:39.800 --> 19:41.560
It was meant to be routine.

19:44.440 --> 19:47.160
I had a buyer in London
for some motorcycles.

19:48.400 --> 19:51.720
I asked my men to steal me four bikes
with petrol engines.

19:54.200 --> 19:56.080
I'm guessing my men were drunk.

19:56.880 --> 19:59.880
<i>Theres a still inside the factory
makes tramline gin.</i>

20:03.840 --> 20:05.920
<i>They picked up the wrong fucking crate.</i>

20:07.480 --> 20:10.320
<i>The boys dropped it
at Charlie Strongs yard, as agreed.</i>

20:11.160 --> 20:15.360
<i>Must have taken it from the
proofing bay, instead of the export bay.</i>

20:20.880 --> 20:23.200
Holy sweet baby of Mary.

20:23.520 --> 20:26.240
Inside we found 25 Lewis machine guns,

20:27.160 --> 20:28.880
10,000 rounds of ammunition,

20:30.040 --> 20:34.080
50 semi-automatic rifles,
200 pistols with shells.

20:34.320 --> 20:35.320
Jesus, Tommy.

20:36.800 --> 20:37.880
All bound for Libya.

20:39.760 --> 20:42.640
Sitting right there
in Charlie Strong's yard.

20:45.560 --> 20:46.880
Tell me you threw them in the cut.

20:48.480 --> 20:50.200
We put them in the stables
out of the rain.

20:51.120 --> 20:53.400
The guns hadn't been greased yet.

20:57.680 --> 20:59.520
So that's why they sent a cop
from Belfast?

21:00.880 --> 21:02.280
Maybe, maybe not.

21:04.800 --> 21:08.280
Thomas, you're a bookmaker,
a robber, a fighting man.

21:08.360 --> 21:09.920
You're not a fool.

21:10.000 --> 21:12.840
You sell those guns to anyone who has
use to them, you will hang.

21:12.920 --> 21:13.920
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

21:19.280 --> 21:20.800
Dump them somewhere
the police can find them.

21:21.720 --> 21:24.000
Maybe if they know they haven't fallen
into the wrong hands,

21:24.080 --> 21:25.800
this might blow over.

21:26.960 --> 21:29.320
-Tell Charlie to dump them tonight.
-No.

21:30.080 --> 21:32.440
He won't move contraband
under a full moon.

21:32.880 --> 21:34.720
Three days until it wanes.

21:35.600 --> 21:36.600
Then you'll do the right thing?

21:40.240 --> 21:41.680
You have your mother's common sense.

21:42.640 --> 21:43.720
But your father's devilment.

21:45.200 --> 21:46.800
I see them fighting.

21:47.880 --> 21:49.400
Let your mother win.

22:39.200 --> 22:41.000
I got tickets for the penny crush.

22:41.280 --> 22:42.840
They're showing a Tom Mix picture.

22:44.240 --> 22:46.320
I'm not in the mood
for the pictures tonight, Ada.

22:46.400 --> 22:49.280
Well, I'm not doing it here again.
I got covered in mud last time.

22:49.640 --> 22:50.680
Let's just walk a bit.

22:51.280 --> 22:53.480
If we go down as far as Greet,
we could go to a pub.

22:54.760 --> 22:56.440
Your brothers have friends in Greet.

22:56.960 --> 22:59.000
They have friends everywhere,
we'd have to walk to London.

22:59.200 --> 23:02.200
I'm with you 'cause you're the
only man round here not scared of them.

23:02.880 --> 23:04.360
Oh, I'm scared of them all right.

23:04.920 --> 23:07.200
But you love me
more than you fear them, right?

23:09.000 --> 23:11.000
I don't want to be
always sneaking about.

23:12.520 --> 23:14.720
-Soon, we'll tell them.
-When?

23:19.280 --> 23:20.680
How did the family meeting go?

23:24.120 --> 23:25.120
Usual.

23:25.720 --> 23:27.600
-There's a new copper coming.
-I heard.

23:27.880 --> 23:28.920
Mmm.

23:29.000 --> 23:31.040
And Tommy says
he's after the likes of you.

23:31.680 --> 23:35.640
So maybe you should burn your books
and stop making speeches.

23:36.400 --> 23:37.520
Oh, my Ada.

23:38.360 --> 23:42.000
The only princess of the Royal Family
of the kingdom of Small Heath.

23:42.840 --> 23:45.520
I'm just a poor communist frog
with a big mouth.

23:50.000 --> 23:51.520
Give me a kiss, Princess Ada.

23:51.720 --> 23:52.720
(ADA GIGGLES)

24:35.120 --> 24:36.920
I'm here about the job as a barmaid.

24:40.160 --> 24:42.160
-Are you mad?
-Am I what?

24:42.480 --> 24:45.760
-Do you know about this place?
-I saw it in an advertisement.

24:46.320 --> 24:48.680
-Job's been filled.
-It was in yesterday's paper.

24:49.400 --> 24:52.160
Believe me, love,
I'm doing you a favour.

24:52.320 --> 24:54.800
I'm not asking for favours,
I'm asking for employment.

24:58.720 --> 25:01.480
You're too...nice.

25:02.600 --> 25:04.440
-How would you know?
-And too pretty.

25:05.360 --> 25:06.720
They'd have you up against a wall.

25:07.640 --> 25:10.720
I have experience. And references.

25:15.840 --> 25:18.640
-What part of Ireland are you from?
-Galway.

25:18.880 --> 25:19.880
Oh.

25:20.480 --> 25:21.480
I worked in Dublin.

25:22.880 --> 25:24.280
Me mother was from Galway.

25:27.960 --> 25:28.960
You're too pretty.

25:29.760 --> 25:30.760
Watch.

25:32.000 --> 25:33.400
And listen.

25:35.480 --> 25:37.760
<i># I wish I was</i>

25:38.400 --> 25:41.520
<i># In Carrickfergus</i>

25:42.200 --> 25:44.320
<i># Only for nights</i>

25:44.720 --> 25:46.800
<i># In Ballygrand</i>

25:47.320 --> 25:50.520
<i># I would swim over</i>

25:50.880 --> 25:53.680
<i># The deepest ocean</i>

25:54.520 --> 25:56.480
<i># The deepest ocean</i>

25:56.800 --> 25:58.960
<i># My love to find</i>

26:00.000 --> 26:02.800
<i># My boy hood friends</i>

26:03.240 --> 26:05.640
<i># And my own relations</i>

26:06.320 --> 26:08.480
<i># Have all passed on now</i>

26:09.120 --> 26:12.160
<i># Like the melting snow #</i>

26:15.080 --> 26:16.080
(GASPS)

26:16.960 --> 26:18.560
In Ireland...

26:18.640 --> 26:20.840
my singing made them cry
and stopped them fighting.

26:22.800 --> 26:24.440
Well, I hope you know a lot of songs.

27:14.240 --> 27:18.760
Babies discarded

27:18.920 --> 27:21.080
with the fish bones and egg shells.

27:23.160 --> 27:24.160
Girls,

27:25.760 --> 27:27.400
11 years old,

27:28.840 --> 27:31.760
pierced and punctured by old men

27:31.840 --> 27:33.280
for thrupence a time.

27:34.120 --> 27:36.080
Rutted upon like animals.

27:37.880 --> 27:38.960
Degradation.

27:40.320 --> 27:42.520
Fathers with their daughters,

27:42.600 --> 27:45.360
brothers and sisters sharing beds.

27:45.960 --> 27:48.680
Beggars and thieves
left to run in the streets.

27:49.880 --> 27:55.520
And astride the whole stinking pile
of wounds and rotting flesh...

27:56.960 --> 27:58.280
your masters!

27:59.800 --> 28:02.320
The men who you touch your cap to.

28:04.720 --> 28:06.440
The Peaky Blinders!

28:08.880 --> 28:12.880
The vicious, merciless gangs

28:12.960 --> 28:15.520
who blind those that see

28:15.600 --> 28:18.000
and cut out the tongues
of those who talk.

28:19.920 --> 28:22.080
You are worse than them!

28:25.360 --> 28:29.160
Those of you who have taken their
bribes these years since the war.

28:29.720 --> 28:32.720
Those of you who look the other way.

28:32.800 --> 28:36.000
You are worse than them!

28:38.400 --> 28:41.600
God damn you for soiling your uniforms!

28:45.280 --> 28:49.280
And then...
there are the IRA Fenians.

28:50.560 --> 28:52.000
And the communists.

28:52.960 --> 28:54.720
Blacker hearts still.

28:55.720 --> 28:58.920
They feed on the pus
of all this corruption.

28:59.400 --> 29:01.760
Like maggots in a corpse.

29:03.240 --> 29:08.320
And, like maggots, if left to swell
they will eventually swarm like flies

29:08.400 --> 29:13.880
and spread their rotten philosophy
across the country and across the world!

29:14.680 --> 29:16.240
Those then...

29:17.560 --> 29:19.200
are our enemies.

29:20.840 --> 29:22.800
A three-headed beast.

29:22.880 --> 29:24.920
It is my job...

29:25.000 --> 29:27.920
to decapitate each one,
and by God I will do it!

29:31.720 --> 29:34.240
I don't trust any of yo use

29:35.200 --> 29:37.520
until you earn my trust.

29:40.000 --> 29:41.480
And that takes some earning.

29:46.360 --> 29:50.000
These are the new men
who will bolster your ranks.

29:52.200 --> 29:53.600
Good men,

29:54.040 --> 29:55.680
from God-fearing families.

29:58.280 --> 29:59.720
By the time the sun sets...

30:00.880 --> 30:03.120
they will be sworn in
and in uniform.

30:03.200 --> 30:06.880
And by sunrise tomorrow
they will be on the streets.

30:11.200 --> 30:13.600
God help those who stand in our way!

30:19.080 --> 30:20.200
Sorry, Mr Shelby.

30:21.160 --> 30:22.160
Right.

30:22.440 --> 30:23.960
WOMAN:
Move out of the way for Mr Shelby.

30:24.040 --> 30:25.560
-This way.
-Mr Shelby.

30:27.600 --> 30:31.240
You see, ladies,
when you're out with a Blinder

30:31.320 --> 30:32.520
you don't have to queue.

30:36.680 --> 30:37.760
Right.

30:38.680 --> 30:42.440
I want a blow job off both of you
before they let the ordinary people in.

30:42.960 --> 30:44.840
Away you go.
Take your hat off.

30:45.120 --> 30:46.360
What the fuck!

30:47.120 --> 30:49.000
Who the fuck are you?

30:49.840 --> 30:52.200
I'm Arthur fucking Shelby!

31:15.320 --> 31:16.320
Arthur Shelby.

31:17.320 --> 31:19.440
Lead pack dog

31:19.520 --> 31:21.200
of the Peaky Blinders.

31:22.440 --> 31:23.440
(GROANS)

31:32.880 --> 31:34.320
Look at me.

31:47.200 --> 31:48.200
(COUGHS)

31:57.120 --> 31:58.280
Bastard!

32:02.480 --> 32:03.800
Your uniform?

32:04.640 --> 32:06.200
Terrifying, I'm sure.

32:07.520 --> 32:09.400
-Did he have a gun?
-No gun.

32:09.800 --> 32:13.120
Knife in his sock.
Cosh in his belt.

32:17.040 --> 32:18.240
Now, Mr Shelby,

32:20.320 --> 32:24.320
I want you to see this
as me introducing myself to you,

32:24.400 --> 32:26.400
you understand.

32:27.480 --> 32:30.920
In all the world,
the only thing that interests me

32:31.880 --> 32:33.320
is the truth.

32:37.920 --> 32:39.680
What do you know about the robbery?

32:40.880 --> 32:42.080
What robbery?

32:44.600 --> 32:45.600
(GROANS)

32:51.400 --> 32:53.240
I will ask you again.

32:54.520 --> 32:57.680
What do you know about the robbery?

32:57.760 --> 33:01.280
I swear to God, I don't know
what you're talking about.

33:01.800 --> 33:03.760
What fucking robbery?!

33:05.280 --> 33:07.320
(GROANS LOUDLY)

33:15.280 --> 33:18.640
After 35 years of dealing
with animals like you,

33:19.560 --> 33:22.720
I can tell just by sniffing the air

33:22.800 --> 33:24.640
whether or not you're lying.

33:26.320 --> 33:28.720
I'm not fucking lying, all right?

33:28.800 --> 33:30.680
I'm not fucking lying!

33:39.520 --> 33:40.520
I know.

33:45.200 --> 33:48.560
I see nothing of interest
behind the blood in your eyes.

33:49.800 --> 33:53.000
And no blood in your veins
that could carry...

33:53.080 --> 33:56.600
even a trace of cunning or guile.

33:58.840 --> 34:00.640
But understand this.

34:02.680 --> 34:04.880
It is well within my power

34:05.800 --> 34:08.440
to have you
and the rest of your scum family

34:09.760 --> 34:12.880
face down in the canal
before the year is out.

34:16.320 --> 34:17.920
On the other hand...

34:21.720 --> 34:23.520
we can help each other.

34:38.000 --> 34:39.680
Is it always this busy in the day time?

34:39.760 --> 34:42.280
Nah, these boys
are on their way to St Andrews.

34:42.400 --> 34:44.680
-To pray?
-(LAUGHS) That'll be the day!

34:44.760 --> 34:47.520
St Andrews is a football ground.
The Blues are playing.

34:47.640 --> 34:49.000
That's the forward line there,

34:49.120 --> 34:50.920
and that's the goalie,
believe it or not.

34:51.760 --> 34:52.760
Hello!

34:57.720 --> 34:59.280
I need a bottle of rum.

34:59.440 --> 35:01.560
Grace, whatever it is,
it's on the house.

35:02.080 --> 35:03.320
-A whole bottle?
-Yeah.

35:03.680 --> 35:05.160
-White or dark rum?
-Don't care.

35:05.240 --> 35:07.280
HARRY: Right, lads, what'll it be? Two?

35:09.040 --> 35:10.480
Thank you.

35:12.600 --> 35:14.800
Harry said it's on the house.

35:16.360 --> 35:17.360
Are you a whore?

35:21.640 --> 35:23.600
'Cause if you're not,
you're in the wrong place.

35:31.040 --> 35:32.680
He's one of them you warned me about.

35:32.840 --> 35:35.880
Look, Grace, you're a friendly girl,
but be careful.

35:36.440 --> 35:37.680
If I say something's on the house,

35:37.760 --> 35:39.440
then say nothing
to whoever you're serving.

35:39.920 --> 35:41.760
If they decide that they want you,

35:41.840 --> 35:44.320
then there's nothing
anybody could do about it.

35:44.720 --> 35:46.960
Lucky for you,
since he got back from France

35:47.080 --> 35:48.840
Tommy doesn't want anybody at all.

35:49.200 --> 35:50.200
Yes, lads?

35:51.880 --> 35:52.880
(GROANS)

35:53.840 --> 35:55.000
John, wipe the blood out of his eye.

35:55.480 --> 35:57.760
-Since when did you give orders?
-I'm a trained nurse.

35:57.960 --> 35:59.840
(SCOFFS) Don't make me laugh.

35:59.920 --> 36:01.800
-It hurts me face.
-I bloody am.

36:02.160 --> 36:04.680
You went to one first aid class
in the church hall

36:04.760 --> 36:06.080
and got thrown out for giggling.

36:06.160 --> 36:08.560
Not before I learned
how to stop somebody from choking.

36:08.640 --> 36:10.240
I'm not bloody choking, am I?

36:10.320 --> 36:12.800
You will be when I wrap this cloth
round your neck.

36:14.200 --> 36:15.400
Let me see him.

36:16.240 --> 36:17.400
All right, have this.

36:20.720 --> 36:21.720
Give me that.

36:25.200 --> 36:26.720
(INHALES SHARPLY)

36:26.800 --> 36:28.600
TOMMY: You're all right.

36:30.160 --> 36:32.440
He said Mr Churchill sent him
to Birmingham.

36:34.480 --> 36:35.880
National interest, he said.

36:36.760 --> 36:38.440
Something about a robbery.

36:42.440 --> 36:44.040
He said he wants us to help him.

36:44.120 --> 36:45.120
We don't help coppers.

36:45.680 --> 36:47.960
He knew all about our war records.

36:48.680 --> 36:50.160
He said we're patriots.

36:50.800 --> 36:52.080
Like him.

36:53.000 --> 36:56.080
Wants us to be his eyes and ears.

36:57.960 --> 36:59.560
I said...

36:59.640 --> 37:01.280
(GROANS)

37:01.360 --> 37:05.800
I said we'd have a family meeting,
take a vote.

37:13.640 --> 37:15.080
Well, why not? Hmm?

37:16.200 --> 37:18.880
We've no truck with Fenians
or communists.

37:24.480 --> 37:25.800
What's wrong with you?

37:27.240 --> 37:29.480
What the fuck is wrong with him lately?

37:29.840 --> 37:32.520
If I knew, I'd buy the cure
from Compton's chemists.

37:34.400 --> 37:37.440
<i># I am just a young girl</i>

37:37.520 --> 37:40.120
<i># I have just come over</i>

37:40.400 --> 37:42.760
<i># Over from the country</i>

37:42.880 --> 37:45.800
<i># Where they do things big</i>

37:46.560 --> 37:49.120
<i># And amongst the boys</i>

37:49.200 --> 37:52.560
<i>#lve got myself a lover</i>

37:52.960 --> 37:56.600
<i># And since I have a lover</i>

37:56.680 --> 37:59.560
<i># I don't care a fig</i>

38:00.080 --> 38:05.800
-(ALLJOINING IN)
<i>.# The boy I love is up in the gallery</i>

38:05.880 --> 38:11.000
<i>.# The boy I love is looking at me</i>
-(MEN STOP SINGING)

38:11.440 --> 38:14.320
<i># Cant you see him standing there?</i>

38:14.520 --> 38:17.800
<i># Waving his handkerchief</i>

38:17.920 --> 38:21.240
<i># As merry as a robin</i>

38:21.320 --> 38:23.760
<i># That sings on the tree #</i>

38:32.400 --> 38:34.440
We haven't had singing in here
since the war.

38:36.400 --> 38:38.680
Why do you think that is, Harry?

38:41.880 --> 38:44.200
(MOANING)

39:11.880 --> 39:13.560
So, did Arthur say, er...

39:15.360 --> 39:17.880
what kind of a deal
this new copper offered him?

39:18.280 --> 39:22.520
God! The second your balls are empty,
it's back onto politics.

39:30.840 --> 39:32.040
What did Tommy say?

39:32.280 --> 39:34.480
He didn't say anything.
You know what he's like.

39:34.840 --> 39:36.120
Yeah, I know what he's like.

39:36.520 --> 39:38.360
Likes to take his fights onto the mud.

39:38.920 --> 39:40.280
Doesn't like to stand and wait.

39:41.000 --> 39:43.160
You know what he'd do
if he found out about us?

39:43.240 --> 39:44.360
He could try.

39:45.240 --> 39:48.040
Sometimes it's like you're with me
just to show you can.

39:52.280 --> 39:54.560
One day me and Tommy
will be on the same side again.

41:01.560 --> 41:03.480
(EXHALES)

41:15.880 --> 41:17.320
Tommy!

41:19.600 --> 41:21.400
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

41:22.080 --> 41:23.080
No!

41:24.960 --> 41:25.960
(GASPS)

41:27.200 --> 41:29.440
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

42:04.280 --> 42:05.920
(SHUDDERING)

42:11.720 --> 42:13.360
(SHUSHING)

42:15.320 --> 42:17.000
(GIBBERING)

42:17.800 --> 42:19.280
(ITALIAN ACCENT) hey, what you do?

42:19.360 --> 42:20.680
-We're closed.
-(SOBBING)

42:21.280 --> 42:22.280
Go home.

42:23.840 --> 42:26.160
-Go home, crazy man.
-They're gonna kill me!

42:26.280 --> 42:27.920
I say go home, crazy man.

42:28.560 --> 42:30.000
(SPEAKING IN ITALIAN)

42:30.080 --> 42:32.840
-They're gonna kill me!
-I said, go home.

42:32.960 --> 42:34.800
Big spiders!

42:36.160 --> 42:37.600
(GIRLS SCREAMING)

42:45.960 --> 42:48.480
(PEOPLE SHOUTING IN ITALIAN)

43:08.800 --> 43:11.880
Secretary of State,
this is Chief Inspector Campbell.

43:17.320 --> 43:18.880
Mr Churchill, sir.

43:20.080 --> 43:22.080
May I say what a great hon our it is
to meet you.

43:22.400 --> 43:24.600
Bit of a whistle-stop tour.

43:25.000 --> 43:27.520
-Love the hat, by the way.
-Thank you.

43:29.480 --> 43:30.480
It's beaver.

43:32.360 --> 43:34.640
So, how are you settling in?

43:36.280 --> 43:37.640
I've set up a command network.

43:37.920 --> 43:40.120
I've agents in place across the city,

43:40.480 --> 43:42.040
who will act as my eyes and ears.

43:43.480 --> 43:47.440
And I've begun to interrogate suspects
vigorously.

43:48.720 --> 43:50.320
You were in Belfast.

43:50.920 --> 43:53.800
Understand you broke
a few Fenian hearts.

43:55.040 --> 43:56.240
A rat's nest, sir.

43:56.520 --> 43:58.760
So, who do you think stole the guns?

43:59.040 --> 44:00.640
The Fenians or the communists?

44:00.960 --> 44:02.800
If it is the IRA Fenians,

44:03.600 --> 44:05.840
I will find them and find the guns.

44:06.160 --> 44:09.240
If it is the communists,
I will find them and find the guns.

44:09.560 --> 44:12.960
If it is common criminals,
I will find them and find the guns.

44:14.000 --> 44:17.000
To me, there is no distinction
between any of the above.

44:18.160 --> 44:21.280
Now, I chose you
because you're effective.

44:21.360 --> 44:23.560
But remember this, Mr Campbell -

44:23.640 --> 44:25.720
this is England, not Belfast.

44:26.040 --> 44:29.000
Bodies thrown in the rivers
wash up in the papers here.

44:29.920 --> 44:33.320
You must keep the existence of these
stolen guns out of the news,

44:33.400 --> 44:36.160
otherwise we are simply
advertising them for sale.

44:37.440 --> 44:39.520
If there are bodies to be buried...

44:40.840 --> 44:41.840
dig holes.

44:43.080 --> 44:44.520
And dig them deep.

44:46.360 --> 44:48.160
I want everything accounted for.

44:48.240 --> 44:49.920
Down to the last bullet.

45:03.880 --> 45:05.440
TOMMY: Uncle Charlie.

45:05.520 --> 45:07.040
A word.

45:07.120 --> 45:08.120
Get aboard.

45:08.920 --> 45:09.920
There's no moon.

45:11.160 --> 45:13.680
We can take them out to the
turning point beyond Gas Street

45:13.760 --> 45:15.120
and leave them on the bank.

45:15.720 --> 45:18.440
They'll be found by railwaymen,
first thing.

45:24.920 --> 45:25.920
Is that agreement?

45:29.080 --> 45:30.640
I changed my mind.

45:32.000 --> 45:33.080
You what?

45:35.160 --> 45:37.120
I've an alternative strategy.

45:39.160 --> 45:41.720
Tell Curly to take her out
to the old tobacco wharf.

45:42.320 --> 45:44.880
There's a lock-up mooring
we used to keep cigarettes.

45:45.160 --> 45:46.160
He knows it.

45:47.160 --> 45:50.600
When the boat leaves your yard,
it's no longer your concern.

45:53.160 --> 45:55.200
Have you lost your fucking mind?

45:56.040 --> 45:57.480
Have you not seen the streets?

45:57.600 --> 46:00.120
They've sent a fucking army
to find these things.

46:00.240 --> 46:01.520
That's right.

46:01.800 --> 46:03.040
They've shown their hand.

46:03.640 --> 46:04.680
Their hand?

46:04.760 --> 46:07.320
If they want them back this bad,
they'll have to pay.

46:07.600 --> 46:09.160
That's the way of the world.

46:09.960 --> 46:12.040
Fortune drops something
valuable into your lap,

46:12.120 --> 46:14.120
you don't just dump it
on the bank of the cut.

46:17.320 --> 46:18.880
You're blood, Tommy.

46:20.160 --> 46:22.200
I've always looked out for you
like a dad.

46:25.240 --> 46:27.760
You're going to bring
only hell down on your head.

46:29.800 --> 46:31.560
This copper takes no prisoners.

46:32.960 --> 46:34.400
I'm told he didn't serve.

46:36.080 --> 46:37.560
Reserved occupation.

46:41.000 --> 46:43.280
Is it another war
you're looking for, Tommy?

46:44.720 --> 46:46.080
The tobacco wharf.

46:47.880 --> 46:49.840
By order of the Peaky Blinders.

47:21.480 --> 47:22.840
Are you in position?

47:26.080 --> 47:27.200
I am, sir.

47:29.000 --> 47:30.240
First impressions?

47:31.560 --> 47:33.960
I'm quite shocked
at how these people live.

47:37.200 --> 47:39.440
Have you found anything out
that might help me?

47:39.640 --> 47:41.840
I interrogated the head
of the Peaky Blinders.

47:42.800 --> 47:43.920
He didn't know anything.

47:44.520 --> 47:45.520
A brute.

47:45.920 --> 47:49.280
It strikes me that it isn't Arthur
who heads the Shelby family.

47:49.720 --> 47:51.400
It's the younger one.

47:51.600 --> 47:52.760
Thomas.

47:55.040 --> 47:57.480
They say he won two medals
for gallantry in the war.

47:58.640 --> 48:00.240
You sound fascinated.

48:03.040 --> 48:05.840
However, my opinion has not changed.

48:07.040 --> 48:08.800
The bookmaker gangs have other business

48:08.880 --> 48:11.320
and the communists
are too weak to have planned this.

48:13.600 --> 48:15.840
I believe the guns
were taken by the IRA.

48:18.520 --> 48:22.840
You must not let your personal history
cloud your judgement.

48:27.640 --> 48:28.640
What history?

48:31.000 --> 48:35.000
That the IRA murdered my father
will not affect my judgement.

48:39.440 --> 48:40.960
If you see any guns,

48:42.080 --> 48:43.840
check the serial numbers
against that list.

48:48.520 --> 48:49.760
Your father...

48:50.240 --> 48:52.960
was the finest officer
I ever worked with.

48:53.960 --> 48:56.240
I know he'd be very, very proud of you.

49:26.240 --> 49:29.400
Danny, as you know,
the man you killed was Italian.

49:31.120 --> 49:34.040
Those two men over there
are his brothers.

49:36.920 --> 49:38.800
If I let the Italians do this, Danny,

49:40.040 --> 49:42.320
they'll cut off your manhood
and let you drain.

49:43.520 --> 49:45.520
That's how those bastards do things.

49:47.560 --> 49:50.560
So, to stop a war breaking out
between us and the Italians,

49:52.880 --> 49:55.000
to save you from their barbarity,

49:58.440 --> 49:59.960
I said I would dispatch you myself.

50:02.920 --> 50:04.360
They're here to witness.

50:12.080 --> 50:14.280
I died over there anyway, Tommy.

50:15.720 --> 50:17.560
I left my fucking brains in the mud.

50:21.800 --> 50:23.680
Do you have any last requests, comrade?

50:29.560 --> 50:33.240
You look out for my Rosie and my boys.

50:35.400 --> 50:36.760
See they get apprenticeships.

50:37.520 --> 50:39.960
At the BSA factory or the Austin.

50:43.320 --> 50:45.360
And they'll make foremen,
I know they will.

50:47.360 --> 50:49.480
Just...ordinary.

50:50.560 --> 50:52.160
Just ordinary men.

50:53.040 --> 50:55.000
And they won't get told to do this shit.

50:56.080 --> 50:59.480
This shit...
This shit that we got told to do!

51:01.560 --> 51:03.400
(WHIMPERING)

51:11.920 --> 51:13.840
I suppose I ought to pray now.

51:17.800 --> 51:19.280
Those fucking guns,

51:20.560 --> 51:22.640
they blew God right outta me head.

51:29.080 --> 51:30.760
Is that boat for me?

51:34.760 --> 51:37.000
We have to get your body
out of the city, Danny.

51:37.600 --> 51:38.720
This new copper, you know.

51:39.000 --> 51:41.000
Don't bury me anywhere there's mud.

51:41.480 --> 51:42.480
Okay?

51:43.440 --> 51:44.440
Promise me.

51:47.280 --> 51:49.080
Bury me on a hill,

51:49.360 --> 51:51.240
and tell Rosie where.

51:54.640 --> 51:56.400
You're a good man,

51:57.280 --> 51:59.120
and a good soldier.

52:02.600 --> 52:04.440
Yes, Sergeant Major.

52:26.200 --> 52:27.800
In the bleak mid-winter...

53:17.560 --> 53:19.600
ARTHUR: Where are ya?

53:22.960 --> 53:24.360
It bloody won.

53:24.720 --> 53:27.120
Monaghan Boy bloody won!

53:28.720 --> 53:31.040
Yeah. It won.

53:32.560 --> 53:34.000
And word will spread.

53:34.720 --> 53:36.480
So the next time we do the powder trick,

53:36.560 --> 53:39.680
it won't be just a garrison
that'll bet on the horse.

53:39.760 --> 53:41.560
It'll be the whole of Small Heath.

53:41.640 --> 53:43.160
And you know what?

53:44.040 --> 53:45.800
The horse will win again.

53:45.880 --> 53:49.400
And the third time we do it we'll have
the whole of Birmingham betting on it.

53:49.480 --> 53:52.960
A thousand-quid bet on the magic horse.

53:53.040 --> 53:54.680
And that time...

53:55.400 --> 53:57.200
when we are ready...

53:57.280 --> 53:58.640
the horse will lose.

54:02.760 --> 54:04.280
Think about it.

54:42.800 --> 54:44.400
CHARLIE: You okay, Danny?

54:44.480 --> 54:45.640
I'm still in shock.

54:47.920 --> 54:49.320
Are you sure this isn't heaven?

54:50.240 --> 54:52.120
If it was heaven,
what would I be doing here?

54:55.920 --> 54:57.680
Tommy wanted you to think it was real.

54:58.280 --> 55:00.040
Try and knock some sense into you.

55:01.160 --> 55:03.280
A shell full of sheep brains
hurts pretty bad.

55:03.360 --> 55:04.640
Aye, it was meant to.

55:07.200 --> 55:08.760
So, where are you taking me?

55:08.840 --> 55:10.120
London.

55:10.200 --> 55:11.920
Tommy has a little job for you.

55:12.000 --> 55:14.480
Give you a chance to say thanks.

55:18.400 --> 55:20.200
You're a Peaky Blinder now, Danny.

55:33.800 --> 55:34.920
POLLY: Bad week?

55:37.280 --> 55:38.840
Heard there was no moon last night.

55:39.520 --> 55:43.760
-I checked. Did you do the right thing?
-Yes, I did the right thing.

56:43.840 --> 56:49.920
<i># Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track #</i>

56:49.944 --> 56:54.944
http://hiqve.com/
